The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Joseph Conrad Arber, who was a sergeant of Calcutta Police in 1946-47, visited the Lalbazar headquarters with his two sons, Simon and Paul, on Friday. He met deputy commissioner (headquarters) Anuj Sharma and other officers. The 78-year-old said after the visit that the force now is much better than the one he had served. He had left Calcutta Police to join Royal Air Force (UK), from where he retired as squadron leader. 

 Traffic in the city was disrupted for several hours on Friday, as members of the CPI-ML (Kanu Sanyal faction) and a religious group organised a demonstration and a march to protest George W. Bush?s visit to India. Police said around 700 members of the religious organisation assembled on Rani Rashmoni Avenue at noon and marched to the US consulate. Around 175 members of the CPI-ML demonstrated at the crossing of Kyd Street and Jawaharlal Nehru Road around 4 pm. 

 The authorities of Bengal Engineering and Science University, Shibpur, had to call in the police following a ?commotion? among some students on Friday, a day after two students? unions were elected. 

 university official said a section of students had questioned some of the decisions taken by the authorities on Thursday. The cops, however, were not allowed to enter the campus, as the ?differences? were resolved at a meeting between the authorities and the students.

 A Divine Service Ceremony will be conducted by M.W. Bro. Arun Chintopanth, Grand Master of Grand Lodge of Ancient, Free and Accepted Masons of India, at Freemasons? Hall on March 4. Swami Satyamayananda, of Ramakrishna Mission, will attend the service.

 Sheikh Feroz, 26, a resident of Moukhali, under Howrah?s Jagachha police station, died after being knocked down by a truck in Santragachhi around 12.30 pm on Friday. Police said the driver fled with his vehicle.

 Nidhan Singh, 35, committed suicide by consuming poison at his residence in Ichhapur, under Howrah?s Jagatballavpur police station, around 1 am on Friday. An unnatural death case has been registered.

 A woman was detained by police after her year-old son was found dead at her residence in Tiljala on Friday. Police said the woman gave incoherent statements during interrogation. 

 Puja Sinha, 15, was injured after she fell off a private bus on route DN 17 on SN Banerjee Road on Friday. She was admitted to NRS Medical College and Hospital.

